article.headline: Mazzante scores 33 to end Terrapins streak
article.linkText: Mazzante, Nittany Lions serve Maryland first loss
article.story: COLLEGE PARK, Md. (AP) -- Kelly Mazzante had just scored 33 points to help No. 8 Penn State hand Maryland its first loss, and Terrapins coach Brenda Frese had obviously seen enough. "I'm ready for her to graduate," Frese said, sighing. With Mazzante leading the way, the Nittany Lions pulled away in the second half to an 82-65 victory Wednesday night. As a sophomore, Mazzante had a career-high 49 points against a Minnesota team coached by Frese. On this night, she went 13-for-22 from the field, 5-for-10 from 3-point range and 2-for-2 at the line. "Kelly obviously had a super game," Penn State coach Rene Portland said. The Nittany Lions (4-1) never trailed and finished with a 37-19 rebounding edge. But the game wasn't decided until the second half, when Penn State finally asserted itself against the smaller, younger Terrapins (4-1). Up by two points at the break, the Nittany Lions got eight points from Tanisha Wright and a 3-pointer from Mazzante in a 16-2 run that made it 51-35. "The first five minutes of the second half we showed a lot of energy," Portland said. "We just did a better executing and attacking." Maryland finally made its first field goal of the half with 13:57 remaining, a 3-pointer by Alli Spence. Spence added two more shots from beyond the arc in an 11-2 run that cut the gap to seven, but a 3-pointer by Mazzante and a driving layup by Jess Strom gave Penn State a 12-point cushion with seven minutes left. "Defensively, we just had a lot of breakdowns," Frese said. "I think fatigue played a huge role, too. But give credit to Penn State. That's a great team." Wright scored 13 points and Jessica Brungo had 12 to help the Nittany Lions win their sixth straight against Maryland. But, as is usually the case, Mazzante was the key. "I just knew how important it was for our team to get a win on the road," she said. Spence had a career-high 22 points, including five 3-pointers, and Shay Doron scored 19 for the Terrapins. "It's upsetting to lose a game we could have won," Doron said. "We came out flat in the second half; we can't let that happen." Mazzante had 17 points in the first half and the Nittany Lions outrebounded Maryland 27-9, but Penn State committed 13 turnovers and led by only 35-33. Portland scolded her players at halftime, reminding them that they had already beaten three Top 25 teams this season and had no business losing to an inexperienced Maryland team that went 10-18 last year. "We have a really mature team. I think they knew what was at stake," Portland said. "We're really putting emphasis on road wins this year."
